    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-01-23T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-01-23T10:00:00-05:00" n="563"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d563">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">881.00/2090: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé at Tangier</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Childs</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tangier</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-01-23T16:00:00+01:00"
                            >January 23, 1942—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 6:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>26. The Legation in recent telegrams and despatches has reported various trends
                    indicative of the desire of General Orgaz, High Commissioner of Spain in
                    Morocco, to divorce himself from the pro-Axis foreign policy of Suñer, Spanish
                    Minister for Foreign Affairs.</p>
                <p>An instance of this policy has been the growing cordiality of Spanish officials
                    toward the Legation and the British Consulate General and the alacrity with
                    which various representations on our part relating to our treaty rights have
                    been and are being acted upon to our satisfaction.</p>
                <p>Yencken, Minister Counselor of the British Embassy in Madrid, has just concluded
                    a visit of some days to Tangier and the Spanish Zone during which he saw General
                    Orgaz twice.</p>
                <p>Orgaz was at particular pains to emphasize that Spanish Morocco is neutral in the
                    present conflict and Yencken was much impressed by the fact that several
                    officials stressed Spanish Morocco’s neutrality.</p>
                <p>Yencken stated he had reached the same conclusions as we had regarding the policy
                    of Orgaz and his desire to preserve the <hi rend="italic">status quo</hi> in the
                    western Mediterranean.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Madrid.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Childs</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
